    "## 1. Introduction & Problem Statement\n",
    "\n",
    "### 1.0 Introduction and Problem Statement\n",
    "Carbon emissions from individual daily behaviours are becoming a major contributor to global climate change. However, personal-level behavioural data is still underutilised in sustainability analysis. Malaysia is highly relevant in this context because the country produces carbon emissions above the world average due to dependence on private transportation and increasing energy consumption.\n",
    "\n",
    "This study focuses on analysing daily behavioural records related to transportation methods, electricity usage, dietary habits, renewable energy usage, waste generation, and eco-friendly practices. Understanding these behaviours can help identify the major contributors to personal carbon emissions and encourage more sustainable lifestyles.\n",
    "\n",
    "### 2.0 Main Objective\n",
    "The objective of this study is to identify the lifestyle factors that significantly influence personal carbon footprints and evaluate whether environmentally friendly behaviours can reduce carbon emissions.\n",
    "\n",
    "### 3.0 Key Analytical Questions\n",
    "1. Which behavioural variables are most strongly associated with daily carbon footprint?\n",
    "2. Can an individual's carbon footprint be predicted from behavioural inputs?\n",
    "3. Do individuals naturally cluster into different carbon behaviour profiles?\n",
    "4. What behaviours best classify carbon impact level as Low, Medium, or High?\n",
    "\n",
    "### 4.0 Why We Chose This Dataset\n",
    "This dataset is suitable because it contains both continuous and categorical target variables, allowing regression, classification, and clustering analysis. The dataset also includes multiple sustainability-related behaviours that are highly relevant to environmental studies. With more than 1000 records, the dataset provides sufficient data for meaningful analysis and machine learning tasks.\n"
